'''Yahashira Shrine''' (八柱神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft}} located at 3-140 Yayoi-chō, {{ill|Hekinan|ja|碧南市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Aichi Prefecture|ja|愛知県|12=draft}}. Its former rank under the {{ill|Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|ja|近代社格制度|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|12=draft}} was Gōsha. consecration_year on August 21, 853 (Ninju 3), it served as the guardian shrine of the Tanao community in {{ill|Hekikai District|ja|碧海郡|12=draft}}. Its auxiliary shrine, {{ill|Tanao Gokoku Shrine|ja|棚尾神社|12=draft}}, dedicated to the spirits of war dead, was established in 1931.

== Deities ==
* {{ill|Ame-no-Oshihomimi|ja|正哉吾勝勝速日天忍穂耳命|12=draft}} (Ame-no-Oshihomimi-no-Mikoto)
* {{ill|Amatsuhikone|ja|天津彦根命|12=draft}} (Amatsuhikone-no-Mikoto)

== History ==
[[File:Tanao-jinja-with-torii.jpg|thumb|Auxiliary shrine, {{ill|Tanao Gokoku Shrine|ja|棚尾神社}]]]

The shrine was established on August 21, 853 (Ninju 3), by Shiki Saemon Fujiwara Norisuke, who constructed the {{ill|Hachioji Shrine|ja|八王子宮|12=draft}} on the site.<ref name="tobotobo">[http://www.katch.ne.jp/~hiro32/machi_info/tanao_area/tanao04.htm Yahashira Shrine], "Walking Around Hekinan City."</ref> In 1160 (Eiryaku 1), Nagata Shosei from {{ill|Utsumi|ja|内海町 (愛知県)|12=draft}} in {{ill|Chita District|ja|知多郡|12=draft}}, {{ill|Owari Province|ja|尾張国|12=draft}}, became the head priest.<ref name="tobotobo"/> The Nagata family served as shrine priests until the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新|12=draft}}. 

The nearby {{ill|Saihō-ji Temple (Hekinan)|ja|西方寺 (碧南市)|12=draft}}, originally located within the shrine grounds, was known as Kōshō-ji until 1496 (Meiō 5).<ref name="tobotobo"/> Other historical landmarks include a stone lantern erected in 1827 (Bunsei 10) by Saitō Wasuke, who developed the Maehama New Fields.<ref name="tobotobo"/> The shrine was renamed Yahashira Shrine in 1872 (Meiji 5) and elevated to Gōsha rank in 1884 (Meiji 17). In the same year, a shrine plaque was donated by the calligrapher {{ill|Yamanaka Shintenō|ja|山中信天翁|12=draft}}.

In 1919 (Taishō 8), a taiko bridge was built to commemorate the repayment of the debt for Tanao Bridge over the {{ill|Yahagi River|ja|矢作川|12=draft}}.<ref name="tobotobo"/> Other notable additions include a large torii in 1923 (Taishō 12) and the establishment of Tanao Shrine as an auxiliary shrine in 1931 (Shōwa 6).<ref>[http://www.city.hekinan.lg.jp/material/files/group/7/katarukai20.pdf "Tanao Shrine and the Monument to Loyal Spirits"], "Telling the History of Tanao."</ref>

== Geography ==
The shrine is situated in the southern part of the former Tanao village in {{ill|Hekikai District|ja|碧海郡|12=draft}}, near the southwestern edge of the {{ill|Hekikai Plateau|ja|碧海台地|12=draft}}. Historically, it overlooked the sea, with {{ill|Enokura Bay|ja|衣浦湾|12=draft}} stretching to its south and west. Salt fields were developed along the coast during the Bunroku era (1592–1596), leaving the name Shiobama-chō ("Salt Beach Town") as a legacy. Salt produced here was exported to {{ill|Shinano Province|ja|信濃国|12=draft}} and used for pickling, thanks to its high brine content. The shrine grounds include a well known as "Yayoi Well," whose water quality contributed to the flourishing of the brewing industry in Tanao.

== Visitor Information ==
; Address
* 3-140 Yayoi-chō, {{ill|Hekinan|ja|碧南市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Aichi Prefecture|ja|愛知県|12=draft}}

; Access
* By train: 15-minute walk from {{ill|Hekinan Station|ja|碧南駅|12=draft}} on the {{ill|Meitetsu Mikawa Line|ja|名鉄三河線|12=draft}}

