The shrine is situated in the southern part of the former Tanao village in {{ill|Hekikai District|ja|碧海郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, near the southwestern edge of the {{ill|Hekikai Plateau|ja|碧海台地|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Historically, it overlooked the sea, with {{ill|Enokura Bay|ja|衣浦湾|qq=draft|qq=draft}} stretching to its south and west. Salt fields were developed along the coast during the Bunroku era (1592–1596), leaving the name Shiobama-chō ("Salt Beach Town") as a legacy. Salt produced here was exported to {{ill|Shinano Province|ja|信濃国|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and used for pickling, thanks to its high brine content. The shrine grounds include a well known as "Yayoi Well," whose water quality contributed to the flourishing of the brewing industry in Tanao.

== Visitor Information ==
; Address
* 3-140 Yayoi-chō, {{ill|Hekinan|ja|碧南市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Aichi Prefecture|ja|愛知県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}

; Access
* By train: 15-minute walk from {{ill|Hekinan Station|ja|碧南駅|qq=draft|qq=draft}} on the {{ill|Meitetsu Mikawa Line|ja|名鉄三河線|qq=draft|qq=draft}}

